    public static HotPepper[] setUp(int answer, String[] pepperType) {
    int[] growthRate = {1, 2, 4, 6, 8}; // 1-8
    int[] plantMaturityRate = {12, 14, 16, 18, 20}; // 10-20
    int[] fruitMaturityRate = {1, 2, 3, 2, 1}; // 1-3

    HotPepper[] peppers = new HotPepper[5];
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; i++) {
        peppers[i] = new HotPepper(pepperType[i], growthRate[i], plantMaturityRate[i], fruitMaturityRate[i]);
    }

    System.out.println(Arrays.toString(peppers));
    return peppers;
}





In this, a new HotPepper object is created for every index of the arrays, and the object&#39;s properties are set using the corresponding values from the arrays. The resulting array of HotPepper objects is then printed and returned.

Also, remember that the HotPepper class needs to have a constructor that accepts the String name, int growth rate, int plant maturity rate, and int fruit maturity rate as arguments in order for this code to work. If the HotPepper class doesn&#39;t have such a constructor, you&#39;ll need to add one.

