1. **The overhead of spawning new threads is much larger than your task at hand.** Benefits of parallelism are more pronounced when the task has substantial amount of computation involved or has operations like I/O which take time.
2. Furthermore, **you should try to keep your number of threads according to the number of cores your CPU has**. Simply, spawning more threads won&#39;t help you since you are limited by your hardware resources, It will only increase the overhead for thread creation and switching between threads as well as the number of threads waiting in queue. Here is a resource explaining it in greater detail:
&lt;https://unix.stackexchange.com/a/80427&gt;

