can someone please explain how to solve this problem without using a return statement?

Given a sorted list of integers, output the middle integer. A negative number indicates the end of the input (the negative number is not a part of the sorted list). Assume the number of integers is always odd.

Ex: If the input is: 2 3 4 8 11 -1 
    the output is: Middle item: 4

The maximum number of list values for any test case should not exceed 9. If exceeded, output &quot;Too many numbers&quot;.

Hint: First read the data into an array. Then, based on the array&#39;s size, find the middle item.

```
    import java.util.Scanner; 

    public class LabProgram {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
      Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
      int[] userValues = new int[10];     
      int arrayLength = 0;
      int i;
      int middleInteger;
      
      for (i = 0; i &lt; 10; ++i) {
          userValues[i] = scnr.nextInt();
      
         if (userValues[i] == -1) {
            arrayLength = i + 1;
            break;
         }
         
         if ((i == 9) &amp;&amp; (userValues[i] != -1)) {
            System.out.println(&quot;Too many numbers&quot;);
            return;
         }
      }
      middleInteger = (arrayLength - 1) / 2;
      
      System.out.println(&quot;Middle item: &quot; + userValues[middleInteger]);
    }
    }
```
